<h2 id="set-up-local-git-repo">Set Up Local Git Repo</h2>

<h3 id="navigate-to-the-project-directory">Navigate to the project directory</h3>
<!-- Do a more thorough view of this like looking at file explorer in setting up dev evironment -->
<ol>
  <li>Open a terminal:
    <ul>
      <li><em>For Windows</em>, go to your search bar and type <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">command prompt</code>, and select it. Alternatively, you can use Powershell.</li>
      <li><em>For Mac</em>, locate <strong>Shell</strong> from your launchpad (go back and reveiw this).</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>Change working directory:
    <ul>
      <li><em>For Windows</em>, your current folder location will be something like <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">C:\Users\firstName.lastName&gt;</code>. Type <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">cd</code> followed by the relative (correct term?) path to the jekyll project. For example, <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">C:\Users\firstName.lastName\Documents\Repos\jekyll-project</code>.</li>
      <li><em>For Mac</em>, …</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ol>

<h3 id="initialize-a-git-repo">Initialize a Git Repo</h3>
<ol>
  <li>Type <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">git init</code> to initialize a new git repo that is now tracking your project files.
<!-- It is confusing when switching between regular file explorer to command line --></li>
  <li>Navigate to your project folder using <strong>File Explorer</strong> <em>on Windows</em>, or (add here) <!-- Go over how to add extension for file explorer on Mac--><em>on Mac</em>.</li>
  <li>Confirm the <strong>.git</strong> folder is inside your project folder. If you do not see it, see the next section.</li>
</ol>

<h3 id="verify-location-of-git-folder">Verify Location of Git Folder</h3>
<p>On <em>Windows</em>:</p>
<ol>
  <li>Ensure you are using <strong>File Explorer</strong> (and not Command Prompt), and you are located within your project folder.</li>
  <li>Verify if the <strong>.git</strong> folder is present. If so, skip the next steps. If not, continue.</li>
  <li>Click the <strong>View</strong> tab at the top.</li>
  <li>Click the <strong>Options</strong> drop-down arrow and select <strong>Change folder and search options</strong>.</li>
  <li>Select the <strong>Show hidden files, folders, and drives</strong> radio button.</li>
  <li>Click <strong>Ok</strong>.
    <ul>
      <li>The <strong>.git</strong> folder should now be visible inside your project folder.</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ol>

<p><em>On Mac</em>:</p>
<ul>
  <li>Fill in.</li>
</ul>

<div class="alert alert-info" role="alert"><i class="fa fa-info-circle"></i> <b>Note:</b> If the <strong>.git</strong> folder is still not visible, you likely initialized your git directory either within the parent folder of your project, or within one of your project folders. If you locate the .<strong>git</strong> folder in either of these locations, delete it, then initialize a new git repo from within your project folder. Not initalizing the git repo in your project folder will cause you a massive headache later.</div>

<h3 id="establish-connection-to-remote-repo">Establish Connection to Remote Repo</h3>
<ol>
  <li>Go to <a href="https://dev.azure.com">https://dev.azure.com</a>, sign in to your account (not work account), and open your Jekyll project.</li>
  <li>From inside your project in Azure DevOps, click <strong>Repos</strong>.
    <ul>
      <li>You should be located within the <strong>Files</strong> folder therein.</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>With the HTTPS button selected (usually by default), click the copy button. <!-- Show screenshot -->
    <ul>
      <li>The repo URL is now copied to your clipboard.
<!-- Do this process in source tree next time --></li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>Switch back to your terminal (i.e. Command Prompt/Powershell <em>for Windows</em> or Bash <em>for Mac</em>). <!--bash or shell? --></li>
  <li>Ensure you are located within your project directory.</li>
  <li>Type <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">git remote add origin</code> followed by the URL you copied previously.
    <ul>
      <li>Example: <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">git remote add origin https://outlookUser@dev.azure.com/outlookUser/jekyll-project/_git/jekyll-project</code></li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>Type <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">git remote show origin</code> to confirm the connection between your local repo (on your machine) and the remote repo (in Azure DevOps).
    <ul>
      <li>You may be prompted to sign into Azure.
        <h3 id="commit-files-locally">Commit Files Locally</h3>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>Type <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">git add --all</code> to add the untracked files in your project to the staging area.</li>
  <li>Type <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">git commit -m "first commit"</code> in your command line tool and hit Enter.
    <ul>
      <li>This command commits the project’s tracked files to your local repo. <!-- ALERT! -->They still need to be pushed to the local repo.
        <h3 id="push-local-files-to-remote-repo">Push Local Files to Remote Repo</h3>
      </li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>Type <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">git push --set-upstream origin master</code>.
    <ul>
      <li>This sets the remote repo as “upstream” and pushes your files to the remote repo on Azure.</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
  <li>From inside your project in Azure DevOps, click <strong>Repos</strong>, or refresh the page if you are already there.
    <ul>
      <li>You should now see the project files you pushed from your local git repo to this remote repo in Azure.</li>
    </ul>
  </li>
</ol>

